# Intuition
To find the averages of subarrays, we can utilize the concept of **Partial Sum**. By calculating the partial sum of the input array v, we can efficiently compute the sum of any subarray. By subtracting the sum of the subarray's left boundary (of length k) from the sum of the subarray's right boundary (of length k), we can obtain the sum of the subarray itself. Dividing this sum by 2*k+1 gives us the average of the subarray.

# Approach
1.Initialize the size of the input array v as n.

2.If n is less than 2*k+1, return a new array ans with all elements initialized to -1.

3.Create a vector t of type int64_t and copy the elements of v into it.

4.Calculate the partial sum of t using the partial_sum function from the STL library.

5.Initialize a new array ans of size n with all elements initialized to -1.
6.Iterate over the range from k to n - k - 1:
- Calculate the sum of the subarray using the partial sum array t.
- Subtract the sum of the left boundary subarray (of length k) from the sum of the right boundary subarray (of length k).
- Divide the obtained sum by 2*k+1 to get the average of the subarray.
- Assign the average to the corresponding element in ans.

7.Return the resulting array ans containing the averages of the subarrays.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: **O(n)**

- Space complexity:  **O(n)**
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> getAverages(vector<int>&v, int k) {
        int n=v.size(),e=(2*k+1);vector<int>ans(n,-1);
        if(n<(2*k+1)) return ans;
        vector<int64_t>t(v.begin(),v.end());
        partial_sum(t.begin(),t.end(),t.begin());
        for(int i=k;i+k<n;i++){
            int64_t u=t[i+k];
            if(i-k-1 >=0) u-=t[i-k-1];
            ans[i]=u/e;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

