# Intuition
- We could use two approaches here, first is sliding window and second which I used, is prefix sum. We understand this by reading description and understands that we need to calculate average of specific range in array.

# Approach
- we need to keep in mind that when calculating prfix sum we should use long type instead of int for prefix sum array, it's stated in description that numbers may be bigger than int allows. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
- O(n) - Sinсe we iterates only two times we actually get O(2n), but since constants are discarded we get O(n).

- Space complexity:
- O(n) - same as with time complexity, we use two additional arrays one for result and second for prefix, we could mutate nums array for results after we calculate prefix sum, but mutating input data is considered bad approach.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[] getAverages(int[] nums, int k) {
        // declare result array of nums.length
        int[] result = new int[nums.length];
        // fill it with -1
        Arrays.fill(result, -1);
        // declare prefix sum arra with nums.length + 1
        long[] prefix = new long[nums.length + 1];
        // set 0th element of prefix sum as 0
        prefix[0] = 0;
        // calculate prefix sum
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            prefix[i + 1] = prefix[i] + nums[i];
        }
        // iterate over nums array, from k to nums.length - k, since we need only viable ranges
        for(int i = k; i < nums.length - k; i++) {
            // calculate sum by taking prefix sum for right boundary + 1(i + k + 1) and subtracting prefix sum for left boundary(i - k)
            long sum = prefix[i + k + 1] - prefix[i - k];
            // now calculate average, cast it to int and place in result array
            result[i] = (int)(sum / (k * 2 + 1));
        }
        // return result
        return result;
    }
}
```

