# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Let's see the example:

Take a vector of size 8: ```[1,1,1,1,**1**,1,1,1]```

Take the ```1``` at index $$4$$.
$$(i-4)=(4-4)=0$$ 
$$(i+4)=(4+4)=8$$
But for Array of size 8, the $$lastindex = 7$$
Thus answer will entirely be ```[-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1]```

So you require the size of given array to be at least: $$2*k+1$$
So in our example, `k=4`, we require an array of at least size 9.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Window size is always $$(i-(i-k))+((i+k)-i)+1 = 2*k+1$$
- Array must be of size minimum $$2*k+1$$
- Have 3 pointers: one back element, one current element, one right element
- When you shift the window, add right element, subtract left element 
[Classic Sliding Window]
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)

- Space complexity: O(1) 
[Because answer requires an array so array not counted in space complexity]

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    // k=4
    // [1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1] (At least 9 required)
    // window always of size (2*k+1)
    vector<int> getAverages(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n=nums.size(),window_size=2*k+1;
        vector<int> v(n,-1);
        if(n<window_size) return v;

        int l,cur,r; //pointers
        unsigned long long sum=0; //track sum
        l=0-k,cur=0,r=cur+k;

        while(l<0) sum+=(nums[cur++]+nums[r++]),++l;
        sum+=nums[r]; // add the last r element that you couldn't add when l reached 0

        //you can also do - keep the while loop condition as (l<=0)
        //then "sum-=nums[l];" after loop completes because:
        //duplicate addition as l reaches index of initial r

        while(r<n)
        {
            if(cur<n) v[cur]=sum/window_size;
            sum-=nums[l];
            if(r+1<n) sum+=nums[r+1];
            else break; //reached right end of array, end
            l++,r++,cur++;
        }
        return v;
    }
};
```

