# Intuition
After seeing the question the thing that came to my mind was that we have to maintain a sum for a window of length 2*k+1 and two edge cases i.e. if window length is greater than the given array nums we have to return an array with all element as -1 and if k is equal to 0 we have to return original array as raidus formed will be 1 with window size 1 that is original array itself.

# Approach
I initialised an array of size n and with all element -1, checked for edge cases and straight away went on the calculation part.
I declared two variables i for checking window length and j for iterating the ans array for storing ans.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)

- Space complexity:
O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> getAverages(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n = nums.size();
        long sum = 0; //to overcome overflows for int
        vector<int> ans(n,-1); //initialising ans vector with -1 and size n
        if((2*k+1)>n) return ans; //check for window size greater than given array
        if(k==0) return ans = nums; //check for window size = 1
        for(int i=0, j=k; i<n; i++) { //initialising loop to traverse the nums array and variable ifor checking window size and j to store average in ans array
            sum += nums[i]; // adding the upcoming elements of nums
            if(i>=2*k) { //checking if i has become greater or equal to required window size
                ans[j++] = sum/(2*k+1); // calculating average from window length and storing it and incrementing j operator for next iteration for next index
                sum -= nums[i-2*k]; // subtracting the first element so that it retains window size for next iteration
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

