# Intuition
By initially seeing this que first thought that should cross our mind is we need the sum of no between k-i to k+i , So all number with index
(0 to k-1 and (n-k)to n-1) will always have -1  as there ans .Hence then we just need to iterate from k to n-k-1 .

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
First we will make suffix vector and prefix vector  both will store sum from end and start respectively. So at index i the sum of i-k to
 i+k  will we equal to 

      (suffix[i-k]+prefix[i+k]-suffix[i]-prefix[i]+nums[i])

and no of element will we 

                        (2*k+1)

so average will we

    (suffix[i-k]+prefix[i+k]-suffix[i]-prefix[i]+nums[i])/ (2*k+1)



# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(N)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

    O(3N)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> getAverages(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n=nums.size();
        vector<int>ans(n,-1);
        vector<long long>p(n,0),s(n,0);
        p[0]=nums[0];
        s[n-1]=nums[n-1];
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            p[i]=p[i-1]+nums[i];
        }
        for(int j=n-2;j>=0;j--){
            s[j]=s[j+1]+nums[j];
        }
        int no=(2*k)+1;
        for(int i=k;i+k<n;i++){
            long long  sum=(s[i-k]+p[i+k]-s[i]-p[i]+nums[i]);
            sum=(sum)/no;
            ans[i]=sum;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

