# Approach
To calculate the avg of the centre element first need to calculate sum up `K+K+1` element 
Keep the `start` variable at `zero` postion initially
Initialize the `avg` vector to -1
Iterate over the nums array when encounter a index `i > k+k`means there is a centre element and has k elements in before and after it
Calculate the avg at that index
Substract value at start index from `sum` So that sum always contain sum of `k+k+1` element
update `start` to next index


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
 O(N)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> getAverages(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        vector<int>avg(nums.size(),-1);
        long long sum=0;
        int start=0,n=k+k+1;
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            sum+=nums[i];
            if(i>=k+k){
                avg[i-k]=sum/n;
                sum-=nums[start];
                start++;
            }
        }
        return avg;
    }
};
